sually don’t appear in single SVO sentences such as “*the sky is is blue.” “Double-is” in relatively short sentences with no clauses are judged unacceptable by speakers.%0a%3c %0a%3c Some linguists argue that “double-is” is not a grammatical construction but a common speech error. However, Coppock et al. found that the first is must be spoken in a more prominent way than the second, which does not fit the typical pattern of mid-speech corrections, and it is highly consistent when speakers are asked to repeat the same sentence. Thus, “double-is” is more likely a grammatical construction than a simple speech error.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source:%0a%3c https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/double-is%0a%3c %0a%3c Coppock, Elizabeth, and Laura Staum. "Origin of the English double-is construction." Manuscript, Stanford University (2004).%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: A:)%0a%3c (:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
